    "154737714": {
      "title": "Dyke Maintenance and Other Stories: Some Neglected Types of Public Goods",
      "abstract": "The orthodox \"summation\" model of a pure nonexcludable public good assumes that each individual consumes a quantity of public good defined as the sum of all individuals' contributions to that good. Recently, Hirshleifer [1983, 1985] has analyzed models that do not fall within this class. At one extreme is the \"weakestlink,\" in which the total quantity available to each consumer equals the smallest individual contribution. At the other is the \"best-shot,\" in which the total quantity available equals the largest individual contribution. Hirshleifer's example of the weakest-link case concerns a circular region, of which each citizen owns a pie-shaped slice. The perimeter is marked by a dyke. Floods may penetrate the weakest point of the dyke and cause damage equally throughout the region. Each citizen decides the height and state of repair of that section of the dyke adjoining his piece of land, its maintenance constituting his contribution to the public good. Thus, the level of protection enjoyed by all is determined by the least well maintained section of the dyke. An example of the best-shot case concerns a number of antimissile batteries ringing a city, firing at an incoming ICBM. All that matters is the accuracy of the best shot. Bliss and Nalebuff [1984] discuss dragon-slaying as another example of a best-shot situation. Section II of this paper introduces a class of functions of which the summation, weakest-link, and best-shot are examples. Section III analyzes the properties of equilibrium when consumers have identical tastes and incomes. Section IV analyzes the implications of income redistribution. In the summation case the equilibrium is unaffected by the initial redistribution over a range, and outside that range transfers help the recipient and hurt the donor. Within the broader class of models, however, the invariance property does not generally hold, and there may be opportunities for Paretoimproving income redistribution. I give an example, similar to the weakest-link case, in which a Pareto-improving redistribution is"
    }
  },
